Combining Datasets

Preparing Our Data

Dataset from here: https://www.kaggle.com/kumarajarshi/life-expectancy-who. We keep the columns: country, life expectancy, and gdp per capita.

life <- read_csv("life.csv")
## 
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   Country = col_character(),
##   Status = col_character()
## )
## ℹ Use `spec()` for the full column specifications.
life <- life[c(1,4,17)]
life <- drop_na(life)

We group the data together by averaging out each country’s information. These will be aggregated over the years from 2000 - 2015

life <- aggregate(life[, 2:3], list(life$Country), mean)
names(life) <- c("Country", "LifeExpectancy", "GDPperCapita")

Do the same for our happiness dataset:

data2015 <- read_csv("archive/2015.csv")
## 
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## cols(
##   Country = col_character(),
##   Region = col_character(),
##   `Happiness Rank` = col_double(),
##   `Happiness Score` = col_double(),
##   `Standard Error` = col_double(),
##   `Economy (GDP per Capita)` = col_double(),
##   Family = col_double(),
##   `Health (Life Expectancy)` = col_double(),
##   Freedom = col_double(),
##   `Trust (Government Corruption)` = col_double(),
##   Generosity = col_double(),
##   `Dystopia Residual` = col_double()
## )
data2019 <- read_csv("archive/2019.csv")
## 
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## cols(
##   `Overall rank` = col_double(),
##   `Country or region` = col_character(),
##   Score = col_double(),
##   `GDP per capita` = col_double(),
##   `Social support` = col_double(),
##   `Healthy life expectancy` = col_double(),
##   `Freedom to make life choices` = col_double(),
##   Generosity = col_double(),
##   `Perceptions of corruption` = col_double()
## )
names(data2015) <- c("Country", "Region", "Rank", "Happiness", "SE",
                     "Economy", "Social", "Health", "Freedom", "Trust",
                     "Generosity", "Dystopia")
names(data2019) <- c("Rank", "Country", "Happiness", "Economy", "Social",
                     "Health", "Freedom", "Generosity", "Trust")
data2015 <- data2015 %>% select("Country", "Happiness", "Economy", "Health")
data2019 <- data2019 %>% select("Country", "Happiness", "Economy", "Health")

databoth <- rbind(data2015, data2019)

databoth <- aggregate(databoth[, 2:4], list(databoth$Country), mean)

names(databoth) <- c("Country", "Happiness", "EconomyContr", "HealthContr")

Now let’s try to combine our dataset from happiness with our dataset of life expectancy and gdp per capita.

data <- merge(life, databoth, by="Country")

Exploring Our Data

Let’s make this longer and more graphable

data %>%
  select(-c("Country")) %>%
  arrange(desc(Happiness)) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c("LifeExpectancy", "GDPperCapita", "Happiness", 
                        "EconomyContr", "HealthContr"),
               names_to = "Category",
               values_to = "Score")
## # A tibble: 670 x 2

Just kidding may not need that, but let’s try happiness vs contribution and happiness vs actual for both categories (GDP / Health).

Health

data %>% ggplot(aes(x=LifeExpectancy, y=Happiness)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_smooth() + 
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("Happiness Score vs Life Expectancy") 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

data %>% ggplot(aes(x=HealthContr, y=Happiness)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_smooth() + 
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("Happiness Score vs WHO Contribution Score for Health") 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

GDP

data %>% ggplot(aes(x=GDPperCapita, y=Happiness)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_smooth() + 
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("Happiness Score vs GDP Per Capita") 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

data %>% ggplot(aes(x=EconomyContr, y=Happiness)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_smooth() + 
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("Happiness Score vs WHO Contribution Score for Economy") 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
